{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17591944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17591944"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:09:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:09:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15222"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15222","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15222"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.43,0.39,0.04,0.04,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7913"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68514"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7913"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15222"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53971"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7662"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8137"},{"type":"tags","id":"9507"},{"type":"tags","id":"10959"},{"type":"tags","id":"11066"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19279"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19283"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68514","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68514"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe development of colorectal cancer typically follows a well-defined sequence of genetic alterations known as the adenoma-carcinoma pathway. Understanding this sequence is crucial for developing targeted therapies and prevention strategies.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the correct sequence of genetic changes in the adenoma-carcinoma pathway?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Loss of APC gene followed by KRAS mutation then chromosome 18 loss","KRAS mutation followed by loss of APC gene then chromosome 18 loss","Loss of chromosome 18 followed by KRAS mutation then loss of APC gene","Loss of APC gene followed by chromosome 18 loss then KRAS mutation","KRAS mutation followed by chromosome 18 loss then loss of APC gene"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe adenoma-carcinoma pathway in colorectal cancer follows a specific sequence of genetic alterations. The initiating event is \u003Cstrong\u003Eloss of APC gene\u003C/strong\u003E, which disrupts the WNT signalling pathway and leads to hyperproliferation of colonic epithelium. This is followed by \u003Cstrong\u003EKRAS mutation\u003C/strong\u003E, which promotes cell growth and survival, driving progression to intermediate adenomas. Finally, \u003Cstrong\u003Echromosome 18 loss\u003C/strong\u003E, which contains important tumour suppressor genes like SMAD4, occurs during progression to late adenomas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other sequences are incorrect because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKRAS mutation followed by loss of APC gene then chromosome 18 loss\u003C/strong\u003E - APC loss must occur first to initiate the pathway\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELoss of chromosome 18 followed by KRAS mutation then loss of APC gene\u003C/strong\u003E - This sequence is completely reversed\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELoss of APC gene followed by chromosome 18 loss then KRAS mutation\u003C/strong\u003E - KRAS mutation occurs before chromosome 18 loss\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKRAS mutation followed by chromosome 18 loss then loss of APC gene\u003C/strong\u003E - This sequence does not reflect the established progression\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditional mutations in p53 and other genes typically occur later in the sequence, promoting invasion and metastasis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The adenoma-carcinoma sequence in colorectal cancer begins with APC gene mutation, which initiates the formation of early adenomas","KRAS mutation is the second major event, promoting progression to intermediate adenomas","Loss of chromosome 18, containing tumour suppressor genes, occurs later and drives progression to late adenomas"],"references":["Meseeha M, Attia M. Colon Polyps. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430761/","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Sandler RS. Epidemiology and risk factors for colorectal cancer. Gastroenterol Clin North Am. 1996 Dec;25(4):717-35. doi: 10.1016/s0889-8553(05)70271-5. PMID: 8960889","Rawla P, Sunkara T, Barsouk A. Epidemiology of colorectal cancer: incidence, mortality, survival, and risk factors. Prz Gastroenterol. 2019;14(2):89-103. doi: 10.5114/pg.2018.81072. Epub 2019 Jan 6. PMID: 31616522; PMCID: PMC6791134"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53971"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15222"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53971","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53971"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T19:50:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T19:51:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7913"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisio